    slug: "religious-fundamentals-that-every-muslim-should-know-about",
    description: `Religious Fundamentals That Every Muslim Should Know About is an English-language Islamic educational book that provides a clear, systematic, and comprehensive introduction to the essential knowledge that every Muslim is obligated to understand about their faith. The book addresses a critical need in Muslim communities where many individuals, despite being born into Muslim families, may not have received a structured religious education that covers the fundamental principles of Islamic belief, practice, and moral conduct. The author has organized this essential knowledge into a logical progression that begins with the most basic concepts and builds toward more nuanced topics, making the book suitable for readers with varying levels of prior religious education, from complete beginners to those who need to review and consolidate their existing knowledge.

The book is structured around the three fundamental categories of Islamic knowledge that scholars have traditionally identified as obligatory for every Muslim. The first section covers aqeedah (Islamic creed and theology), explaining the six pillars of iman: belief in Allah and His attributes, belief in the angels, belief in the divinely revealed books, belief in the prophets and messengers, belief in the Day of Judgment and the hereafter, and belief in divine decree (qadar). Each pillar is explained with reference to the primary textual sources (the Quran and authentic hadith) and is presented in a manner that avoids both the excessive simplification that can lead to misunderstanding and the complex theological jargon that can be confusing for general readers. The second section covers the fiqh (practical rulings) of the five pillars of Islam: the declaration of faith (shahadah), the five daily prayers (salaat), the fast of Ramadan (sawm), the obligatory charity (zakat), and the pilgrimage to Makkah (Hajj). The rulings are presented according to the mainstream scholarly consensus, with brief mention of major differences of opinion where relevant, so that readers understand that some flexibility exists within the boundaries of Islamic law.

The third section of the book covers Islamic ethics and moral conduct, discussing the essential character traits that every Muslim should cultivate, including honesty, patience, gratitude, humility, kindness, justice, and courage. It also covers the major sins that every Muslim should avoid and the concept of repentance for those who fall into error. The book concludes with practical guidance on how to continue learning about Islam after mastering these fundamentals, recommending specific books, study methods, and resources for further education. The English prose throughout the book is clear and accessible, with Arabic terms transliterated and explained when they first appear. The book is designed to serve as a foundational text for new Muslims, a refresher course for lifelong Muslims, a teaching manual for Islamic schools and weekend programs, and a reference for parents who want to ensure their children receive a sound religious education at home.`,
