    slug: "repent-to-allah",
    description: `Repent to Allah is an English-language Islamic book that provides a comprehensive and spiritually uplifting treatment of the concept of repentance (tawbah) in Islam, addressing one of the most fundamental and universally relevant aspects of the Muslim's relationship with Allah. The book explains the Islamic teaching that no matter how great a person's sins may be, Allah's mercy is greater, and that sincere repentance is always accepted by Allah, as stated in the Quran: "Say, O My servants who have transgressed against themselves, do not despair of the mercy of Allah. Indeed, Allah forgives all sins" (Surah Az-Zumar, 39:53). This message of hope and divine mercy is the central theme of the book, and the author develops it through a thorough examination of the Quranic verses and authentic hadith that deal with repentance, forgiveness, and the boundless mercy of Allah.

The book begins by establishing the theological foundation of repentance, explaining the Islamic understanding of sin, its consequences, and the mechanism through which repentance cancels out sin and restores the sinner to a state of purity. The author explains the three essential conditions of sincere repentance as identified by the scholars: immediate cessation of the sinful act, genuine remorse for having disobeyed Allah, and a firm resolve never to return to the sin. Where the sin involves the rights of another person, a fourth condition is added: restoring the rights of the wronged party or seeking their forgiveness. The book provides detailed guidance on how to fulfill each of these conditions, drawing upon the example of the Prophet (peace be upon him), his companions, and the righteous predecessors who were known for their frequent repentance despite their overall piety and devotion.

The book then addresses the spiritual, psychological, and practical dimensions of repentance. It discusses the barriers that prevent people from repenting, including despair of Allah's mercy, shame, pride, and the fear that repentance will not be accepted. Each barrier is addressed with relevant Quranic verses and hadith that dismantle these misconceptions and encourage the sinner to turn back to Allah. The book also discusses the relationship between repentance and other acts of worship, explaining how prayer, fasting, charity, and other good deeds serve as expiation for sins and how repentance enhances the spiritual value of all acts of worship. Specific chapters address the repentance of different categories of sinners, including those who have neglected their religious obligations, those who have wronged others, those who are struggling with persistent sins, and those who feel overwhelmed by the weight of their past mistakes. The English prose is compassionate and encouraging without compromising the Islamic teaching that sin is serious and repentance is necessary. This book is suitable for anyone who has sinned and wants to return to Allah, as well as for those who counsel and advise others on matters of faith and spiritual purification.`,
